  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of the key ones:\n\n*   **The Vienna Convention (1988):** Officially the United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances. This was one of the first major international agreements that criminalized money laundering derived from drug trafficking. It required signatory countries to:\n    *   Establish money laundering as a criminal offense.\n    *   Adopt measures to identify, trace, freeze, and seize proceeds of drug trafficking.\n    *   Cooperate internationally to facilitate the investigation and prosecution of drug-related money laundering offenses.\n\n*   **The Palermo Convention (2000):** Officially the United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime. This convention expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, including corruption, human trafficking, and terrorism. It requires signatory countries to:\n    *   Criminalize the laundering of proceeds from a wide range of predicate offenses.\n    *   Implement measures for customer due diligence and record-keeping by financial institutions.\n    *   Establish financial intelligence units (FIUs) to receive and analyze suspicious transaction reports.\n    *   Cooperate internationally in investigations, prosecutions, and asset recovery.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** While not a law or treaty itself, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction. It develops and promotes policies and best practices that countries should implement. The FATF's recommendations are widely recognized and adopted by countries around the world. Non-compliance with FATF recommendations can result in a country being placed on a \"grey list\" or \"black list,\" which can have significant economic consequences.\n\n*   **Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime (1990) and its Revised version (2005):** These conventions aim to facilitate international cooperation in combating money laundering and recovering illicit assets. They address issues such as the criminalization of money laundering, the establishment of effective measures for tracing, freezing, seizing, and confiscating assets, and the improvement of international cooperation in these areas.\n\nThese international laws and conventions provide a framework for countries to develop and implement their own domestic laws and regulations to combat money laundering. They also promote international cooperation in the investigation and prosecution of money laundering offenses, and in the recovery of illicit assets.",
